  abstract = {Publisher Summary This chapter focuses on ill-posed problems in partial differential equations. Typically, solutions of ill-posed problems, unless they are appropriately constrained, will not depend continuously on any quantities that are subject to error in the modeling of the problem, and it is never clear a priori that a constraint that will bring about continuous dependence under one type of perturbation will also guarantee continuous dependence under another. For instance, a constraint set restriction that implies continuous dependence on the Cauchy data will not necessarily insure continuous dependence on coefficients. Two major sources of error have been largely ignored in the literature: (1) errors in geometry and (2) errors in modeling. The latter errors are in general more difficult to deal with than the more commonly treated errors in Cauchy data. In fact, it is the inability to adequately regularize against such errors that casts doubt on the entire study of ill-posed problems in partial differential equations as an accurate predictor of what will occur in the physical situation being modeled. Under errors in geometry, there are obvious errors in spatial geometry, but there are types of errors that might result from the fact that not all of the data is measured precisely at time to but rather over some interval of time. The chapter presents some examples of both types of perturbations of geometry.}
}
